# Cursor AI Rules

{{- if eq .profile "work" }}
> **CORPORATE ENVIRONMENT** - Strict compliance mode enabled
{{- end }}

## General Principles

1. **Understand before acting** - Read the relevant code before making changes
2. **Minimal changes** - Only modify what's necessary
3. **Preserve style** - Match existing code conventions
4. **Security first** - Never hardcode secrets or credentials
{{- if eq .profile "work" }}
5. **Compliance** - Follow company policies and standards
6. **Audit trail** - All changes must be traceable
{{- end }}

## Code Quality

- Follow language-specific best practices
- Write self-documenting code; add comments only when logic isn't obvious
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Keep functions small and focused
{{- if eq .profile "work" }}
- All public APIs must have documentation
- Error messages must be actionable
{{- end }}

## Shell Scripts

- Always use `shellcheck` compliance
- Quote variables: `"$var"`
- Use `set -euo pipefail` for scripts
- Prefer `[[ ]]` over `[ ]`

## Git

- Sign commits when configured
- Use conventional commit format
- Keep commits atomic
{{- if eq .profile "work" }}
- Include ticket reference (e.g., JIRA-123)
- Never force push to main/master
- Require PR reviews before merge
{{- end }}

## Testing

- Write tests for new functionality
- Don't break existing tests
- Prefer integration tests over unit tests for complex logic
{{- if eq .profile "work" }}
- Minimum 80% code coverage for new code
- Security tests required for auth/data handling
{{- end }}

## What NOT to do

- Don't add unnecessary dependencies
- Don't refactor working code unless asked
- Don't add comments that just repeat the code
- Don't create files unless necessary
{{- if eq .profile "work" }}
- Don't access external URLs without approval
- Don't store secrets in code or configs
- Don't bypass CI/CD pipelines
- Don't modify infrastructure without review
{{- end }}

{{- if eq .profile "work" }}

## Compliance Checklist

Before submitting code:
- [ ] No hardcoded credentials
- [ ] No PII/sensitive data in logs
- [ ] Input validation on all external data
- [ ] Error handling doesn't leak internal details
- [ ] Dependencies are from approved sources
{{- end }}
